      <div id="main">
                
        <h1>Hacking the Internet of Things</h1>
        <span class="sub">Hardware solutions for everybody</span>
        <p>
          Written by <a href="http://twitter.com/andreareginato">Lelylan Chief</a> | Mar 09, 2012
        </p>
        
 

        <div class="article">

  <ul class="media-grid">
    <li>
      <a href="#">
        <img class="thumbnail" src="/images/blog/hardware/header.png" alt="">
      </a>
    </li>
  </ul>
  
  <p>
    When connecting devices to the web you face different questions. One is for sure to 
    understand which is the best electronic you can use. In Lelylan we are experimenting 
    the definition of physical nodes, devices that defines a set of web services to connect 
    your house to the web.
  </p>

  <p>
    To build a physical node you can use different hardware solutions varying on 
    <a href="http://beyondthekeeboard.wordpress.com/2011/06/25/a-simple-overview-to-help-choose-your-hardware-for-internet-of-things-solutions/">computational power, wireless capability and budget</a>. 
    The only required thing is the possibility to bild a web server that accepts and send 
    request over the internet.
  </p>



  <br/>
  <h2><a href="http://arduino.cc">Arduino</a></h2>

  <ul class="media-grid">
    <li>
      <a href="http://arduino.cc">
        <img class="thumbnail" src="/images/blog/hardware/arduino.png" alt="">
      </a>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    <strong>Category</strong>:
    hacking electronics.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Description</strong>:
    open-source electronics prototyping platform based on flexible, easy-to-use 
    hardware and software. It's intended for artists, designers, hobbyists, and 
    anyone interested in creating interactive objects or environments. It can be
    connected to the internet using 
    <a href="http://store.arduino.cc/it/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=11_12&products_id=141">ethernet</a>, 
    <a href="http://store.arduino.cc/it/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=11_5&products_id=5">zigbee</a>, 
    <a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/products/9954">wifi</a> and more.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Good</strong>:
    big community, open-source hw, cheap, documentation.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Bad</strong>:
    computational power.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Prices</strong>: 
    <strong>base</strong>
      <a href="http://store.arduino.cc/it/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=11_12&products_id=195">~ $30</a>,
    <strong>ethernet</strong>
      <a href="http://store.arduino.cc/it/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=11_12&products_id=141">~ $60</a>,
    <strong>wifi</strong>
      <a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/products/9954">~ $120</a> and
    <strong>zigbee</strong> 
      <a href="http://store.arduino.cc/it/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=11_5&products_id=5">~ $75</a> 
      (including <a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/products/8664">XBee Antenna</a>).
  </p>



  <br/>
  <h2><a href="http://nanode.eu/">Nanode</a></h2>

  <ul class="media-grid">
    <li>
      <a href="http://nanode.eu/">
        <img class="thumbnail" src="/images/blog/hardware/nanode.png" alt="">
      </a>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    <strong>Category</strong>:
    hacking electronics.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Description</strong>:
    open source Arduino-like board that has in-built web connectivity. It connects to a range 
    of wireless, wired and ethernet interfaces. It allows you to develop web based sensor and 
    control systems, giving you web access to six analogue sensor lines and six digital I/O 
    lines. Nanode was designed with hacking in mind.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Good</strong>:
    built-in web connectivity, open-source hw, really cheap, arduino compatible.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Bad</strong>:
    computational power, documentation.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Prices</strong>:
    <strong>ethernet</strong> <a href="http://nanode.eu/buy">~ $40</a> and
    <strong>wireless</strong> <a href="http://nanode.eu/buy">~ $48</a> 
    (uses <a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/products/9582">RFM12B wireless transceiver</a>).
  </p>



  <br/>
  <h2><a href="http://www.openpicus.com">openPICUS</a></h2>

  <ul class="media-grid">
    <li>
      <a href="http://www.openpicus.com">
        <img class="thumbnail" src="/images/blog/hardware/openpicus.png" alt="">
      </a>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    <strong>Category</strong>:
    hacking electronics.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Description</strong>:
    defines itself as Internet freedom for your things, control and communication for 
    electronic devices. A standalone hardware and software platform for embedded applications 
    to interact via web, email or messages with simple sensors or complex electronic equipment.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Good</strong>:
    built-in web connectivity, cheap, good documentation, support.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Bad</strong>:
    computational power, development windows oriented.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Price</strong>:
    <strong>wifi</strong>
    <a href="http://www.eikonsite.it/openpicus/prodotti.aspx?cprod=015365">~ $90</a>.
  </p>



  <br/>
  <h2><a href="http://www.netduino.com">Netduino</a></h2>

  <ul class="media-grid">
    <li>
      <a href="http://www.netduino.com/">
        <img class="thumbnail" src="/images/blog/hardware/netduino.png" alt="">
      </a>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    <strong>Category</strong>:
    hacking electronics.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Description</strong>:
    open-source electronics platform using the .NET Micro Framework. With Netduino, the world 
    of microcontroller programming can be easily aproached by people programming with .NET.  
    Netduino is designed to enable both personal projects and sophisticated commercial endeavors. 
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Good</strong>:
    open-source hw, cheap, documentation, arduino compatible, .NET programming.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Bad</strong>:
    computational power.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Prices</strong>: 
    <strong>base</strong>
      <a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/products/10107"</a>~ $35</a>,
    <strong>ethernet</strong>
      <a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/products/10186">~ $60</a>,
    <strong>wifi</strong>
      <a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/products/9954">~ $120</a> and
    <strong>zigbee</strong> 
      <a href="http://store.arduino.cc/it/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=11_5&products_id=5">~ $75</a> 
      (including <a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/products/8664">XBee Antenna</a>).
  </p>



  <br/>
  <h2><a href="http://www.libelium.com/">Libellium Waspmote</a></h2>

  <ul class="media-grid">
    <li>
      <a href="http://www.libelium.com/">
        <img class="thumbnail" src="/images/blog/hardware/libelium.png" alt="">
      </a>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    <strong>Category</strong>:
    hacking electronics.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Description</strong>:
    sensor device developers oriented. It works with different communicaction protocols 
    (ZigBee, wifi, Bluetooth and GPRS) and frequencies (2.4GHz, 868MHz, 900MHz) and create 
    links up to 12Km. Using the hibernate low power mode (0.7uA) it can save battery energy 
    when not transmitting and be able to work even for years. Waspmote is compatible with 
    more than 50 sensors and its open source IDE makes really easy to start working with it
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Good</strong>:
    documentation, solid, support,
    <a href="http://www.libelium.com/products/waspmote/hardware">radio borads</a>,
    <a href="http://www.libelium.com/products/waspmote/sensors">sensors boards</a>,
    <a href="http://www.libelium.com/products/waspmote/hardware">over the air programming</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Bad</strong>:
    computational power, expensive.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Price</strong>: 
    <strong>zigbee</strong>
    <a href="http://www.libelium.com/products/waspmote"</a>~ $180</a>,
    <strong>wifi</strong>
    <a href="http://www.libelium.com/products/waspmote"</a>~ $200</a>.
    The price catalog can be found <a href="http://www.libelium.com/xhjs76gd/libelium_products_catalogue.pdf">here</a>
  </p>

  </br>
  <h2>Considerations</h2>
  <p>
    This is an opinioned list with the best solutions out there. If you think we are missing
    a good one you can head over to <a href="<%= item[:comments] %>">Hacker News</a> to add it.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is the first part of a two articles serie. In the next one we will be featuring 
    hardware solutions with more computational power like
    <a href="http://www.raspberrypi.org/">Raspberry Pi</a> and
    <a href="http://pandaboard.org/">Panda Board</a>, which are perfect to define hubs that
    communicates with the web and all devices in your house.
  </p>
</div>

        <div class="tag-buttons">
          <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style" 
